TAFFY: You mean the ring finger?

791
00:48:08,085 --> 00:48:09,953
MONICA: Yeah.

792
00:48:10,053 --> 00:48:13,590
For men, it's generally
the other way around.

793
00:48:13,690 --> 00:48:15,559
It is?

794
00:48:15,659 --> 00:48:19,863
The index finger is usually
the same length or even

795
00:48:19,963 --> 00:48:21,431
shorter than the ring finger.

796
00:48:24,134 --> 00:48:25,903
You read that in
Ripley or something.

797
00:48:26,003 --> 00:48:27,671
Naw, it's true.

798
00:48:27,771 --> 00:48:29,273
Does everybody knows this?

799
00:48:32,476 --> 00:48:35,012
I didn't.

800
00:48:35,112 --> 00:48:39,049
Guy named Erwin Reisner
told me about it.

801
00:48:39,149 --> 00:48:41,818
It was this little game
he used to play in bed,

802
00:48:41,919 --> 00:48:43,487
you know, like morning after?

803
00:48:46,456 --> 00:48:50,994
He'd take your hand, and
he'd hold it up to his.

804
00:48:56,433 --> 00:48:59,136
And then he'd show you how
the fingers didn't match up.

805
00:49:02,205 --> 00:49:04,441
It was kind of a
ritual with him.

806
00:49:04,541 --> 00:49:07,210
He'd always do that.

807
00:49:07,311 --> 00:49:09,246
You mean every time
you slept with him?

808
00:49:09,346 --> 00:49:11,281
Hmph, no-- with
different girls.

809
00:49:17,654 --> 00:49:20,424
Erwin Reisner, huh?

810
00:49:20,524 --> 00:49:21,625
Yeah.

811
00:49:21,725 --> 00:49:22,592
Remember that name.

812
00:49:25,796 --> 00:49:27,864
I guess you knew
him pretty well.

813
00:49:27,964 --> 00:49:30,834
No.

814
00:49:30,934 --> 00:49:32,536
I was 18.

815
00:49:32,636 --> 00:49:36,306
Took me right off the
20th Century Limited.

816
00:49:36,406 --> 00:49:39,609
Everything I had read
or heard about Hollywood

817
00:49:39,710 --> 00:49:48,585
was right there, right in
front of me, just waiting.

818
00:49:48,685 --> 00:49:55,892
And before you knew it, we were
playing footsie, and handsie

819
00:49:55,992 --> 00:49:57,060
and everything elsie.

820
00:49:59,463 --> 00:50:01,365
Ain't that just like a man?

821
00:50:01,465 --> 00:50:04,968
Take advantage of a poor,
sweet, innocent young girl?

822
00:50:05,068 --> 00:50:06,603
Oh, I was.

823
00:50:06,703 --> 00:50:09,039
And probably from
a good neighborhood.

824
00:50:09,139 --> 00:50:10,374
Hell's Kitchen, honey.

825
00:50:18,482 --> 00:50:23,854
I wish I were from
someplace glamorous, like you.

826
00:50:23,954 --> 00:50:25,255
10th Avenue and 44th?

827
00:50:28,058 --> 00:50:29,559
That's about as
glamorous as the Argon.

828
00:50:35,065 --> 00:50:38,068
There are no
party decorations--

829
00:50:38,168 --> 00:50:41,805
no balloons, no
streamers, no nothing.

830
00:50:41,905 --> 00:50:45,308
Well, 30's a tricky age
for someone who's standing

831
00:50:45,409 --> 00:50:48,545
in for a 26-year-old actress.

832
00:50:48,645 --> 00:50:52,716
30's a tricky age
for any actress.

833
00:50:52,816 --> 00:50:55,986
32, in fact--

834
00:50:56,086 --> 00:50:58,755
1905.

835
00:50:58,855 --> 00:51:01,391
I saw her passport when
she hopped down to Havana.

836
00:51:03,727 --> 00:51:07,064
That makes her a full six
years older than the fucking

837
00:51:07,164 --> 00:51:10,667
star she's standing in for.

838
00:51:10,767 --> 00:51:11,601
Gosh.

839
00:51:11,701 --> 00:51:13,637
Where's Havana?

840
00:51:13,737 --> 00:51:14,538
Cuba, honey.

841
00:51:14,638 --> 00:51:15,639
Cuba.

842
00:51:15,739 --> 00:51:20,143
Were a gent can fix
his lady's problems.

843
00:51:20,243 --> 00:51:21,678
Oh, that problem.

844
00:51:21,778 --> 00:51:23,780
Yep.

845
00:51:23,880 --> 00:51:24,681
Oh, god!

846
00:51:24,781 --> 00:51:25,615
The sign!

847
00:51:39,129 --> 00:51:43,600
Where the hell is Martha Anne?

848
00:51:43,700 --> 00:51:44,601
Fuck this.

849
00:51:57,948 --> 00:51:59,216
Hey there, blue eyes.

850
00:51:59,316 --> 00:52:01,818
How you doing?

851
00:52:01,918 --> 00:52:03,620
Don't call me blue eyes.

852
00:52:03,720 --> 00:52:05,088
I don't have blue eyes.

853
00:52:05,188 --> 00:52:08,592
Well you ought to, doll.

854
00:52:08,692 --> 00:52:11,761
One of these days, the Swedish
swan is going to need them.

855
00:52:14,297 --> 00:52:16,566
Just two words for you, Shirl.

856
00:52:16,666 --> 00:52:19,236
Techni-- color.

857
00:52:19,336 --> 00:52:22,506
Those two words
don't scare me.

858
00:52:22,606 --> 00:52:28,445
I'm not afraid of Technicolor,
which is one word, by the way.

859
00:52:28,545 --> 00:52:29,412
Hm.

860
00:52:29,513 --> 00:52:30,680
No?

861
00:52:30,780 --> 00:52:32,449
SHIRLEY: No.

862
00:52:32,549 --> 00:52:38,054
So what if I don't have
Greta Garbo's eyes?

863
00:52:38,154 --> 00:52:41,791
Nobody has Garbo's eyes.

864
00:52:41,892 --> 00:52:48,431
Calma started by
projecting red and green.

865
00:52:52,469 --> 00:52:55,839
Technicolor is a
process that suits me.

866
00:52:58,542 --> 00:53:03,914
Those have always been
my colors, red and green.

867
00:53:04,014 --> 00:53:04,981
Stop and go.

868
00:53:09,219 --> 00:53:10,287
Mostly go.

869
00:53:14,791 --> 00:53:22,866
Now our boy Jack here, is
living in little Jackie Turner's

870
00:53:22,966 --> 00:53:29,472
scope, a process developed
at the Palace Theater

871
00:53:29,573 --> 00:53:39,649
in Boise, Idaho, a process
that only Jack sees,

872
00:53:39,749 --> 00:53:44,421
where they take black
and white and turn it

873
00:53:44,521 --> 00:53:50,627
into a blue riddance,
mm, like they did

874
00:53:50,727 --> 00:53:52,596
in "A Midsummer Night's Dream."

875
00:53:55,599 --> 00:53:57,400
What fools these mortals be?

876
00:54:03,039 --> 00:54:08,912
That's why Jack and I
will always be friends,

877
00:54:09,012 --> 00:54:17,053
because he knows about tinting,
and I know about red and green.

878
00:54:24,361 --> 00:54:27,931
So don't call me blue eyes.

879
00:54:28,031 --> 00:54:28,832
They're hazel.

880
00:54:31,801 --> 00:54:33,503
And no.

881
00:54:33,603 --> 00:54:35,639
I'm not afraid of Technicolor.

882
00:54:40,143 --> 00:54:41,044
[ringing]

883
00:54:41,144 --> 00:54:43,880
I'll get it.

884
00:54:43,980 --> 00:54:45,115
Quick, it's Martha Anne!

885
00:54:45,215 --> 00:54:46,950
Help me put these
candles on the cake!

886
00:54:47,050 --> 00:54:47,884
Quickly!

887
00:54:47,984 --> 00:54:48,852
Ernie's Pagoda Lounge.

888
00:54:53,223 --> 00:54:58,261
Oh, it's you.

889
00:54:58,361 --> 00:55:01,698
I can't really talk right now.

890
00:55:01,798 --> 00:55:04,100
The car is fine.

891
00:55:04,200 --> 00:55:05,035
Turn on the radio?

892
00:55:05,135 --> 00:55:06,936
Why?

893
00:55:07,037 --> 00:55:08,371
All right, all right.

894
00:55:14,477 --> 00:55:16,246
PEGGY: OK, for God's
sake, everybody,

895
00:55:16,346 --> 00:55:18,381
please try to be nice to her.

896
00:55:18,481 --> 00:55:20,183
And Shirley, do you
think you could pretend

897
00:55:20,283 --> 00:55:22,285
to be pleased to see her?
Please?

898
00:55:22,385 --> 00:55:25,989
SHIRLEY: I'll be
good, like usual.

899
00:55:30,894 --> 00:55:32,295
MAN (ON RADIO): We
interrupt this program

900
00:55:32,395 --> 00:55:33,263
for a special bulletin.

901
00:55:33,363 --> 00:55:34,264
PEGGY: Happy birthday!

902
00:55:34,364 --> 00:55:35,832
MONICA: Hey glamourpuss!

903
00:55:35,932 --> 00:55:37,634
PEGGY: Happy birthday!

904
00:55:37,734 --> 00:55:40,503
Martha Anne, happy birthday!

905
00:55:40,603 --> 00:55:44,007
MAN (ON RADIO): --and
one on [inaudible]

906
00:55:46,376 --> 00:55:48,745
--opposite Gable
in "China Seas."

907
00:55:48,845 --> 00:55:51,915
But Kansas City native,
born Harlene Carpenter,

908
00:55:52,015 --> 00:55:55,452
succumbed just before noon
today to a cerebral edema

909
00:55:55,552 --> 00:55:57,787
in Los Angeles's Good
Samaritan Hospital.

910
00:55:57,887 --> 00:56:00,790
With her at her bedside where
her mother, and the actor,

911
00:56:00,890 --> 00:56:01,825
William Powell.

912
00:56:01,925 --> 00:56:04,227
Repeating our
bulletin, Jean Harlow,

913
00:56:04,327 --> 00:56:10,433
the blonde bombshell of the
silver screen, is dead at 26.

914
00:56:10,533 --> 00:56:12,569
I need a drink.

915
00:56:22,946 --> 00:56:26,216
I just worked with her
this morning, you know,

916
00:56:26,316 --> 00:56:28,184
on-- on "Saratoga?"

917
00:56:28,284 --> 00:56:30,120
Violet-- that's
Jean's makeup lady.

918
00:56:30,220 --> 00:56:32,422
Sometimes she does
my makeup, too.

919
00:56:32,522 --> 00:56:34,023
Violet told me that the baby--

920
00:56:34,124 --> 00:56:36,593
that's what Violet calls her--

921
00:56:36,693 --> 00:56:40,263
had a premonition
last week sometime.

922
00:56:40,363 --> 00:56:42,432
Anyhow, Violet was
sponging off her face,

923
00:56:42,532 --> 00:56:46,302
and Harlow looked at
her, and said, "Violet?

924
00:56:46,403 --> 00:56:48,505
I have a feeling
I'm going someplace

925
00:56:48,605 --> 00:56:51,641
and I'm never coming back."

926
00:56:51,741 --> 00:56:54,244
Violet thought she
was talking about Palm

927
00:56:54,344 --> 00:56:56,179
Springs or maybe even Europe.

928
00:56:59,649 --> 00:57:02,752
You ever had a
premonition, Jack?

929
00:57:02,852 --> 00:57:06,923
My premonitions were all
about my Hollywood career.

930
00:57:07,023 --> 00:57:09,459
Never coming back.

931
00:57:09,559 --> 00:57:11,995
That sounds really final.

932
00:57:12,095 --> 00:57:13,930
You think she knew?

933
00:57:14,030 --> 00:57:15,999
TAFFY: I believe it.

934
00:57:16,099 --> 00:57:17,100
I really do.

935
00:57:17,200 --> 00:57:19,302
Who the hell are you?

936
00:57:19,402 --> 00:57:21,070
Taffy.

937
00:57:21,171 --> 00:57:22,405
I'm Taffy.

938
00:57:22,505 --> 00:57:25,008
She's Hayworth's new stand-in.

939
00:57:25,108 --> 00:57:25,909
Another one?

940
00:57:33,283 --> 00:57:36,386
Harlow never shared any
her premonitions with me.

941
00:57:36,486 --> 00:57:39,155
Hell, I don't do her makeup.

942
00:57:39,255 --> 00:57:42,392
All I do is stand in her shadow.

943
00:57:42,492 --> 00:57:44,894
Then I stand in her light.

944
00:57:44,994 --> 00:57:48,565
Then I sit down while
Harlow does her scene.

945
00:57:48,665 --> 00:57:51,301
Martha Anne's my name, honey--

946
00:57:51,401 --> 00:57:53,536
just Martha Anne.

947
00:57:53,636 --> 00:57:55,672
TAFFY: Martha
Anne's a nice name.

948
00:57:55,772 --> 00:57:57,674
You think so, huh?

949
00:57:57,774 --> 00:58:02,412
Well, it's a name straight out
of Lake Charles, Louisiana.

950
00:58:02,512 --> 00:58:04,848
All of us are called by
two names down there.

951
00:58:04,948 --> 00:58:07,951
It's a part of their French
tradition or Napoleonic code

952
00:58:08,051 --> 00:58:09,185
or something.

953
00:58:09,285 --> 00:58:12,121
But--

954
00:58:13,957 --> 00:58:17,794
In my case, it was different.

955
00:58:17,894 --> 00:58:21,731
Three years before I
was born, my father

956
00:58:21,831 --> 00:58:24,734
had already taken
a powder for Panama

957
00:58:24,834 --> 00:58:28,304
or some other
equatorial paradise,

958
00:58:28,404 --> 00:58:31,541
and left mom a pair of twins.

959
00:58:31,641 --> 00:58:34,777
There was a fire.

960
00:58:34,878 --> 00:58:38,014
Nobody knows how it started.

961
00:58:38,114 --> 00:58:40,450
There wasn't anybody
there when it ignited,

962
00:58:40,550 --> 00:58:44,721
except those baby twins.

963
00:58:44,821 --> 00:58:48,258
When rescue workers
found them, they thought

964
00:58:48,358 --> 00:58:50,026
they were burnt rag dolls.

965
00:58:50,126 --> 00:58:52,595
Oh, sweet Jesus.

966
00:58:52,695 --> 00:58:53,997
They were my sisters.

967
00:58:57,667 --> 00:59:02,405
My mother had been out
all night conjuring

968
00:59:02,505 --> 00:59:05,575
me up with some truck driver--

969
00:59:05,675 --> 00:59:08,444
was a produce truck, I think.

970
00:59:08,544 --> 00:59:12,315
And I was born 30
years ago today--

971
00:59:12,415 --> 00:59:13,983
June 7, 1907.

972
00:59:17,687 --> 00:59:22,525
My mother hated me
from that day onward.

973
00:59:22,625 --> 00:59:27,263
Soon as I could walk, she would
drag me through the cemetery,

974
00:59:27,363 --> 00:59:31,601
pull me along by the hand
through the tombstones.

975
00:59:31,701 --> 00:59:36,072
I can still remember how
that soft earth would crunch

976
00:59:36,172 --> 00:59:42,178
beneath my feet,
until we'd arrive

977
00:59:42,278 --> 00:59:50,720
at those two tiny matching
headstones for two baby girls--

978
00:59:50,820 --> 00:59:54,958
Martha and Anne.

979
00:59:55,058 --> 01:00:00,129
My momma would stick my nose
in the soft earth of those two

980
01:00:00,229 --> 01:00:05,268
tiny plots and say, "Martha
Anne, if they hadn't died,

981
01:00:05,368 --> 01:00:06,836
you wouldn't be alive."

982
01:00:10,506 --> 01:00:11,307
Martha Anne?

983
01:00:14,010 --> 01:00:17,080
My momma had christened
me Martha Anne.

984
01:00:19,515 --> 01:00:23,686
She used to force my hand into
the engraving on the tombstones

985
01:00:23,786 --> 01:00:27,123
and make me trace their names.

986
01:00:27,223 --> 01:00:32,362
"If they had lived, you
wouldn't have a soul."

987
01:00:32,462 --> 01:00:37,200
She'd make me pray for their
salvation, a special prayer

988
01:00:37,300 --> 01:00:41,404
she had concocted,
offering up my chance

989
01:00:41,504 --> 01:00:44,874
at heaven in
exchange for theirs,

990
01:00:44,974 --> 01:00:50,179
a prayer for their eternal life.

991
01:00:50,279 --> 01:00:55,218
I had to pray that my soul
would be damned to hell

992
01:00:55,318 --> 01:00:57,920
if it meant heaven
for Martha and Anne.

993
01:01:00,790 --> 01:01:03,659
It was a two-for-one deal.

994
01:01:03,760 --> 01:01:06,929
Momma wasn't sure
God would buy it,

995
01:01:07,030 --> 01:01:10,800
but she kept me
praying for 16 years.

996
01:01:13,436 --> 01:01:14,771
I don't know what to say.

997
01:01:14,871 --> 01:01:16,239
Yes you do.

998
01:01:16,339 --> 01:01:18,975
All of you know it.

999
01:01:19,075 --> 01:01:21,277
It's like you were
born to be a stand-in.

1000
01:01:21,377 --> 01:01:28,051
MARTHA ANNE: Jack,
Harlow's dead, but alive

1001
01:01:28,151 --> 01:01:30,653
forever in the
memory of her fans,

1002
01:01:30,753 --> 01:01:35,191
a legend, the platinum blonde.

1003
01:01:35,291 --> 01:01:36,559
Me?

1004
01:01:36,659 --> 01:01:39,062
I'm really dead.

1005
01:01:39,162 --> 01:01:42,165
If it wasn't for
Erwin, my very own man,

1006
01:01:42,265 --> 01:01:47,937
a rotten snake, but all
mine, I really would

1007
01:01:48,037 --> 01:01:49,238
think about killing myself.

1008
01:01:52,708 --> 01:01:55,645
Oh, God!

1009
01:01:55,745 --> 01:01:57,280
I look like death.

1010
01:01:57,380 --> 01:01:59,916
I didn't even
realize I was crying.

1011
01:02:00,016 --> 01:02:02,452
This one's going to
require major surgery.

1012
01:02:02,552 --> 01:02:03,386
Back in a jiff.

1013
01:02:11,727 --> 01:02:13,362
JACK: You think Shirley's right?

1014
01:02:13,463 --> 01:02:14,497
About what?

1015
01:02:14,597 --> 01:02:15,798
About me.

1016
01:02:15,898 --> 01:02:17,967
I mean, all that little
Jackie Turner scope.

1017
01:02:18,067 --> 01:02:19,102
What do you think?

1018
01:02:21,737 --> 01:02:24,507
Maybe there is some
process only I can see.

1019
01:02:24,607 --> 01:02:26,576
She hit a nerve.

1020
01:02:26,676 --> 01:02:30,513
Yeah-- the one in her arm.

1021
01:02:30,613 --> 01:02:32,515
Yes, but in wine
there is truth.

1022
01:02:32,615 --> 01:02:34,016
Think that goes for dope, too?

1023
01:02:34,117 --> 01:02:37,787
Well, don't they make
truth serum with morphine?

1024
01:02:37,887 --> 01:02:40,323
Suppose I do see things
that nobody else can.

1025
01:02:40,423 --> 01:02:43,192
Sweet blood Jesus, Jack.

1026
01:02:43,292 --> 01:02:46,162
You're supposed to be the
normal one around here.

1027
01:02:46,262 --> 01:02:47,997
I'm counting on you to
hold this mess together

1028
01:02:48,097 --> 01:02:49,665
until we can all go
home and just forget

1029
01:02:49,765 --> 01:02:53,002
this night ever happened.

1030
01:02:53,102 --> 01:02:53,903
Jack!

1031
01:02:59,775 --> 01:03:02,145
Some party, huh?

1032
01:03:02,245 --> 01:03:03,713
Where's Monica?

1033
01:03:03,813 --> 01:03:05,314
She went to the valley.

1034
01:03:05,414 --> 01:03:09,118
She had a callback
on "Twelfth Night."

1035
01:03:09,218 --> 01:03:10,419
Yeah, that's what she said.

1036
01:03:13,122 --> 01:03:15,658
You think Monica lied
about her callback?

1037
01:03:15,758 --> 01:03:19,896
Oh, maybe.

1038
01:03:19,996 --> 01:03:21,230
Why would she lie?

1039
01:03:21,330 --> 01:03:25,401
Because she's a fucking
stand-in, that's why.

1040
01:03:25,501 --> 01:03:28,271
PEGGY: She doesn't
always talk like one.

1041
01:03:28,371 --> 01:03:30,106
Well, no.

1042
01:03:30,206 --> 01:03:35,311
No, because Monica fancies
herself as an actress.

1043
01:03:35,411 --> 01:03:37,046
She's ashamed of
being a stand-in.

1044
01:03:39,715 --> 01:03:41,951
Viola's a swell part.

1045
01:03:42,051 --> 01:03:46,589
I played it once, back home
at the Neptune Theater.

1046
01:03:46,689 --> 01:03:47,490
Figures.

1047
01:03:50,760 --> 01:03:54,497
Say, who was that
